<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Coordinate System" class="currentChild" href="Coordinate_System">Coordinate System</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
Any system used to mathematically indicate location. Most coordinate systems utilize two axes (a horizontal, called an <a title="x-Axis" href="x-Axis">x-axis</a>, and a vertical, called a <a title="y-Axis" href="y-Axis">y-axis</a>), coordinates being plotted with respect to variables indicated along both axes. Such a system is known as two-dimensional, as only two variables are mapped; an additional <a title="z-Axis" href="z-Axis">z-axis</a> is often added to add a third dimension. A graph is a basic coordinate system, often using only two axes. Graphics and page layout programs allow objects to be drawn or positioned by means of coordinates. 
</p>
<p id="l3">
In three-dimensional modeling, different sets of coordinates are used: <a title="world coordinates" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/world_coordinates">world coordinates</a> are absolute, fixed coordinates, while <a title="Modeling Coordinates" href="Modeling_Coordinates">modeling coordinates</a> and <a title="Eye Coordinates" href="Eye_Coordinates">eye coordinates</a> are coordinates defined in terms of a particular viewing angle. 
</p>
